**[Summary]**  
The ticket addresses the lack of information regarding the invocation of the function "UpdateDatabaseAfterUpdateSchema" in the context of Web API projects. The solution is to add the relevant information about this process in the documentation.

**[Subject]** When is the function "UpdateDatabaseAfterUpdateSchema" invoked **[Description]** [DevExpress Support Team: CLONED FROM [T1317063: When is the function "UpdateDatabaseAfterUpdateSchema" invoked]({'FriendlyId':'T1317063','HashCode':'','CheckAnswerDesk':'7bb212e9-1af8-4a62-a4b6-fd592cbadb44'})]

## Issue

The [Update Database When Debugging](https://docs.devexpress.com/eXpressAppFramework/112795/deployment/production-database-and-application-updates/update-application-and-database-versions-using-the-module-info-table#update-database-when-debugging) section lacked the information about Web API projects. Such projects call the Module Updater's `Update` method from the `AddBuildStep` method in `Startup.cs`, where the Web API application subscribes to the [XafApplication\.DatabaseVersionMismatch](https://docs.devexpress.com/eXpressAppFramework/DevExpress.ExpressApp.XafApplication.DatabaseVersionMismatch) event:

```cs
            builder.AddBuildStep(application => {
                application.ApplicationName = "SetupApplication.dxT1317063";
                application.CheckCompatibilityType = DevExpress.ExpressApp.CheckCompatibilityType.DatabaseSchema;
#if DEBUG
                if(System.Diagnostics.Debugger.IsAttached && application.CheckCompatibilityType == CheckCompatibilityType.DatabaseSchema) {
                    application.DatabaseUpdateMode = DatabaseUpdateMode.UpdateDatabaseAlways;
                    application.DatabaseVersionMismatch += (s, e) => {
                        e.Updater.Update();
                        e.Handled = true;
                    };
                }
#endif
            });
```

## Solution

Add the missing information about Web API. **[Comments]**  **[Answer]**  **[Note]**

**[Summary]**  
The ticket addresses an issue with the incorrect implementation of the "Type Properties in XPO" help topic, specifically regarding how type properties are declared in a code example. The concern is that filtering based on the `System.Type` property using a specific client approach leads to errors during execution, affecting the operation of a customer project. The proposed solution involves changing the type of the `BILLTYPE` property from an implicit `System.Type` to an explicit `System.String` type and updating relevant documentation. Additionally, a note is included to clarify the limitations of using the implicit approach with `System.Type` in conjunction with `XPO ValueConverter` in criteria expressions.

**[Subject]** Incorrect code for the "Type Properties in XPO" help topic  
**[Description]**  
## Expected Results

1. Filtering for such type properties works without errors in popular DataAccessMode (not only in Client) and Security modes (Middle-Tier and Integrated):

2. Our docs at [https://docs.devexpress.com/eXpressAppFramework/113580/business-model-design-orm/data-types-support…](https://docs.devexpress.com/eXpressAppFramework/113580/business-model-design-orm/data-types-supported-by-built-in-editors/type-properties/type-properties-in-xpo?v=25.2) are updated to modify the System.Type property declaration as follows (from implicit System.Type to an explicit System.String property).  <PERSON>: this code is done for a customer, for the docs please make a more generic naming without <PERSON> (ask <PERSON>, if required).

 ```cs
private string dataTypeName;
 [Browsable(false)]
 [Persistent("BILLTYPE")]
 public string DataTypeName {
     get { return dataTypeName; }
     set {
         Type type = XafTypesInfo.Instance.FindTypeInfo(value) == null ? null :
             XafTypesInfo.Instance.FindTypeInfo(value).Type;
         if (_BILLTYPE != type) {
             _BILLTYPE = type;
         }
         //if (!IsLoading && value != dataTypeName) {

         //}
         SetPropertyValue<string>(nameof(DataTypeName), ref dataTypeName, value);
     }
 }

 private Type _BILLTYPE;
 [TypeConverter(typeof(LocalizedClassInfoTypeConverter))]
 [ImmediatePostData, NonPersistent]
 public Type BILLTYPE {
     get { return _BILLTYPE; }
     set {
         if (_BILLTYPE != value) {
             _BILLTYPE = value;
             DataTypeName = (value == null) ? null : value.FullName;
         }
     }
 }
```

3. Add a red note that the implicit approach with the System.Type property and XPO ValueConverter is not supposed to work. Here is a note from [https://docs.devexpress.com/XPO/DevExpress.Xpo.Metadata.ValueConverter](https://docs.devexpress.com/XPO/DevExpress.Xpo.Metadata.ValueConverter), which can be reused as is:
>Properties persisted using [Value Converters](https://docs.devexpress.com/XPO/2053/create-a-data-model/value-converters) require the client-side conversion logic, and should not be used in [criteria expressions](https://docs.devexpress.com/CoreLibraries/4928/devexpress-data-library/criteria-language-syntax) evaluated on the database server side. An attempt to use such properties in criteria may lead to undefined behavior. For instance, when a criterion is translated to a database query, a conversion implemented programmatically may not be applied or may be applied multiple times.

